Zhang Guangjun was appointed as the deputy governor of Guangdong Province.
The fifth meeting of the Standing Committee of the 13th National People's Congress of Guangdong Province held its second plenary meeting in Guangzhou on the 30th.
After the vote, the meeting decided to appoint Zhang Guangjun as the deputy governor of the Guangdong Provincial People's Government.
Previously, Zhang Guangjun was deputy secretary of the party committee of the China Academy of Engineering Physics.
Comrade Zhang Guangjun's resume: Zhang Guangjun, male, Han Chinese, born in February 1968, Chongqing, joined the party in April 1994, joined the work in July 1991, graduated from the Department of Radio Engineering of Harbin University of Technology, graduated from the Department of Electronic Instrumentation and Measurement Technology, a university degree, a senior engineer, and a special allowance expert from the State Council government.
He is currently a deputy governor of the Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the party group.
1987-1991 Professional study of electronic instruments and measurement technology in the Department of Radio Engineering, Harbin University of Technology
1991-1998 Technical Officer, Deputy Director, Party Branch Secretary and Deputy Director of the General Engineering Research Institute of the China Academy of Engineering Physics
1998-2002 Deputy Director and Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the General Engineering Research Institute of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during which: 1999.05-2000.12 also served as the Secretary of the Discipline Inspection Commission of the Research Institute, 2001.09-2001.12 Sichuan Provincial Party Committee Party School Prefecture-level Cadre Study Course)
2002-2002 Party Secretary and Deputy Director of the Institute of General Engineering of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during which: 2002.03-2004.05 Fudan University School of Management, Graduate Program in Management Science and Engineering)
2002-2009 Director of the Political Department of the China Academy of Engineering Physics, Director of the Party Committee Office, Vice-President of the Party School (during which: 2005.09-2006.01 Young cadres in the Central Party School Training Course)
2009-2014 Director of the Office of Major Special Management Office of the China Academy of Engineering Physics (during which: 2011.09-2012.01 Training Course for Young Cadres in the Central Party School)
2014-2015 Assistant Dean of China Academy of Engineering Physics and Director of the Office of Major Engineering Management
Deputy Secretary of the Party Committee of the China Academy of Engineering Physics 2015-2018
In September 2018, he was appointed deputy governor of the Guangdong Provincial Government and a member of the party group.
According to British media, Admiral William Moran, Undersecretary of Naval Operations, said that even as the U.S. Navy is reviving its forces to deal with an increasingly worrisome Russia on both sides of the Atlantic, the United States continues to focus its naval priorities in the Asia-Pacific region, which the Pentagon has expanded to include the Indo-Asia-Pacific.
According to the British "Jane's Defense Weekly" website reported on September 24, the United States announced at the beginning of the new national defense strategy in the China and Russia as a strategic competitor.
Since then, the U.S. Navy has restored the Second Fleet to more directly counter Russian activities.
The moves have raised some questions and concerns among allies and analysts that the U.S. Navy may stay away from the “Asia-Pacific rebalancing” strategy that marks the Obama administration.
But General Moran said the U.S. Navy remains focused on the Western Pacific.
“There have been no significant changes for us,” he said at a roundtable discussion titled “Responding to the High Seas Challenge,” hosted by the National Bureau of Asian Studies in Washington, D.C., on January 24, 2018.
“The point is still to rebalance, shift your focus, or describe it no matter what you want to describe it,” Moran said.
But he acknowledged that the United States has close ties to Europe.
“We will continue to focus on the growth of the West Coast and balance what we can do,” he said.
While Moran noted that overall policy on Russia falls within the purview of the U.S. defense secretary, he warned: “Russians may face demographic and economic challenges, but history proves that if we clash with them, they will be very tough.”
As part of the U.S. resurgent operation against Russia, China and other competitors, the U.S. Navy is dynamically deploying troops into a "new mode of operation," General Moran said, which will help put adversaries off guard by the deployment of U.S. carrier strike groups or other assets at any given time and place.
“We in the Navy and Marine Corps support it—the concept of operational unpredictability, not to be in the same place again and again, almost like a clockwork—is what we do,” he said.
The first to attempt the new approach was the Harry Truman carrier strike group, whose early deployment included working visits to the port and patrolling the normally only passing areas.
Moran said the U.S. Navy is working to ensure that allies are aware that the ships will still patrol traditional areas and are also addressing logistical and family liaison issues for the new deployment process.
The Royal Australian Navy’s commander, Lieutenant General Michael Noonan, also spoke at the event, saying the Australian military could work seamlessly with the U.S. carrier strike group.
He said that this will continue as the Royal Australian Navy plans to purchase nine more frigates equipped with the Aegis combat system.
From October 5, a number of airlines will raise or resume fuel surcharges, and there will be more money for aircraft travel from next Friday.
Yesterday, Xiangpeng Airlines, Aokai Airlines and other airlines announced that from October 5, 2018 (the date of issuance), the domestic route fuel surcharge of 800 km (inclusive) per passenger to charge 20 yuan fuel surcharge, more than 800 kilometers per passenger to charge 30 yuan fuel surcharge.
Xiangpeng Airlines, Aokai Airlines and other companies announced that from 0:00 (the ticketing date) on October 5, 2018, the fuel surcharge for domestic routes below 800 kilometers (inclusive) increased from 10 yuan / person to 20 yuan / person, and the fuel surcharge for domestic routes above 800 kilometers increased from 10 yuan / person to 30 yuan / person per passenger.
Children and military and police disabled are 10 yuan / person; infants continue to be exempted.
According to the person in charge of Ctrip's ticket, the airline has indicated in the notice that the fuel surcharge is charged on the original ticket date, and when the ticket is changed, the fuel surcharge is not refunded.
This means that the domestic route ticket issued before October 5th, if it is to be changed to October 5 (inclusive), it is not necessary to pay fuel surcharges according to the new standard.
Since June 5, 2018, Air China, China Eastern Airlines, HNA, Shanghai Airlines, Spring Airlines, Shenzhen Airlines, Western Airlines, Aokai Airlines and other airlines have resumed charging fuel surcharges for domestic routes that have been cancelled for three years, and the standard is 10 yuan / person.
This time, Xiangpeng Airlines and Aoke Airlines took the lead in announcing the increase in fuel surcharges, and as of the press release, they have not yet seen the news that the domestic four major airlines have announced follow-up adjustments.
It is also understood that the Civil Aviation Department of Hong Kong stipulates that airlines can decide whether to charge fuel surcharges from November.
Cathay Pacific announced as early as September 27 that it will re-charge fuel surcharges from November 2.
According to the Cathay Pacific website, all Cathay Pacific and Cathay Dragon Airlines tickets issued or reissued on or after November 2 will include a fuel surcharge, long-distance flights to and from Hong Kong and the South-West Pacific, North America, Europe, Middle East and India, Africa, fuel surcharge of $652, short-haul flights charge 146 yuan.
The fee applies to all types of tickets, is calculated on each segment and is included in the ticket quotes for all direct distribution channels in Cathay Pacific.
