People's Daily Beijing, November 5 (Wang Xiaoyan) under the current wave of "mass entrepreneurship, innovation", more and more technology companies began to attach importance to patent research and development and related protection work, digging deep into the potential value of patents, occupy the market dominance.
Similarly, many technology companies have encountered a lot of infringement in the licensing of patented technologies and the use of patented technologies.
At the end of 2017, Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Lai Bin from Guangdong Province sued the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court of Beijing Xiaoqing Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as "Xiao orange technology), the operator of Didi Travel Technology Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Didi Travel) and the seller Guangdong Pacific Internet Information Service Co., Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Guangdong Pacific) on the grounds of patent infringement.
The three plaintiffs requested the court's order that the three defendants immediately stop manufacturing, selling, promising sales, and using the plaintiff's patent behavior.
On October 30, 2018, China Judgment Documents Network announced the "Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Beijing Xiaoqing Technology Co., Ltd. and other infringement patent rights dispute first instance civil ruling", disclosed the details of some cases of Didi Travel APP being sued for patent infringement.
The three plaintiffs believe that the patentee and the inventor of the patent based on the mobile terminal's ride-sharing service system and methods, and the entire operation process of the "windmill" application in the "Didi Travel" APP corresponds to the technical solution of patent protection involved, which constitutes patent infringement.
However, during the court ruling, Xiaoqing Technology believes that Guangdong Pacific is not a qualified defendant, which only provides a free download of the APP "Didi Travel" involved on the network, does not implement the patented method involved, does not directly or indirectly infringe, and should not be listed as a defendant in this case.
Second, the infringement in this case is not in Guangdong.
According to the law, the infringement of the patent involved should be the place where the patent method involved is fully implemented, so it raised objections to the jurisdiction of the court and asked to transfer the case to the court of the defendant's domicile, that is, the Beijing Intellectual Property Court.
The Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court held that the defendant Guangdong Pacific provided the accused of infringement of the drip travel APP products on its online platform, and the plaintiff listed the defendant Guangdong Pacific as a defendant.
And the defendant Guangdong Pacific residence in Guangzhou, belongs to the jurisdiction of the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court.
The defendant Xiaoqing Technology advocated that the case be transferred to the Beijing Intellectual Property Court for trial, and on the basis of insufficientness, the defendant Xiaoqing Technology Co., Ltd. rejected the objection to the jurisdiction of the case, and bear the cost of accepting the jurisdictional objection case.
At present, the other trials of the case have not yet been announced, and the reporter will pay close attention to the follow-up details of the Didi Travel patent infringement case.
Interview with the CEO of the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization: the results of the Australia-China scientific and technological cooperation are remarkable
"China's science and technology has developed rapidly in the past few decades, and Australia and China can achieve fruitful results together in the field of science."
Larry Marshall, chief executive of the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization, said in an interview with China News Agency in Beijing that from the cooperation of climate change to the "eye of the sky" project, the cooperation between Australia and China in the field of science and technology has shown vitality.
As the largest national scientific research institution in the Commonwealth of Australia, CSIRO has achieved many innovative research results in the fields of oceans, energy, biology, materials, and astronomy.
CSIRO has maintained close cooperation with scientific research institutions such as the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
“It’s an enduring friendship that embraces a tradition of trust and long-term cooperation with partners,” Marshall said.
In May this year, China's 500-meter diameter spherical radio telescope, "China's Eye", installed the world's first 19-beam L-band receiver.
At present, the most advanced 19-beam feeder in the world is jointly developed by Chinese and Australian scientists.
Marshall said that the successful development of the receiver is based on the CSIRO's many years of technology accumulation, after the opening, the FAST survey speed will be increased by 5 to 6 times, at the same time, will also expand more scientific observation targets.
"This is a contribution of CSIRO to FAST."
In addition to the above cooperation, CSIRO also cooperates closely with Chinese scientific research institutions in the construction of square kilometers of array radio telescopes, the development of new fuel technologies, and energy conservation and emission reduction.
"In the past, scientific research often focused on the problems of hundreds of years later, and now more scientific research is needed to solve the problems in front of us."
Marshall believes that Australia and China are complementary in the field of scientific development, and both countries face a series of challenges in development.
For example, extreme weather is frequent around the world, droughts and floods have led to food production, and food shortages have seriously affected human development.
At the same time, population explosion, aging, chronic diseases and other issues are also serious challenges currently facing.
"The cooperation between Australia and China in recent years is mainly aimed at solving these current problems."
According to Marshall, the International Marine Research Center for the Southern Hemisphere, jointly built by CSIRO and the Qingdao National Laboratory of Marine Science and Technology, focuses on observing the El Niño phenomenon and the La Niña phenomenon, studying the relationship between the two and extreme weather, and establishing an early warning facility for extreme weather; the new grain varieties jointly developed by CSIRO and the Chinese Academy of Sciences to overcome extreme weather can also alleviate the food shortage caused by extreme weather.
"In the current environment, scientific and technological innovation is difficult to complete alone, the need for extremely high costs, to solve a lot of problems, so cooperation is particularly important today."
Marshall said that the closer the cooperation, the more likely it is that it will make a breakthrough, which is also the significance of strengthening cooperation between Australia and China under the framework of the Belt and Road Initiative.
"Strengthening bilateral cooperation is mainly for us scientific and technological cooperation."
Marshall said, for example, CSIRO recently developed a non-cyanide gold purification method, because the traditional cyanide gold purification method is very harmful to the environment, many countries hope to find a small amount of environmental pollution of gold purification method.
"We are very willing to introduce this technology to China, which is one of the achievements of our participation in the Belt and Road cooperation."
