North Korea's foreign minister, Ri Yong-ho, told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening North Korea's distrust of the United States, and that it was impossible for North Korea to unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Mr. Ri said at the U.N. General Assembly that North Korea had taken a “very friendly approach” over the past year, including halting missile and nuclear tests, dismantling nuclear test sites and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"But we haven't seen any corresponding response from the U.S.," he said.
"If we don't trust the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and in such a situation, we can't unilaterally give up weapons first."
While Mr. Ri repeated North Korea’s complaint that the United States opposes “phased” denuclearization, his speech was of great significance because it did not completely reject unilateral denuclearization, as North Korea had previously done.
Mr. Li referred to a joint statement by Mr. Kim and Mr. Trump on June 12, when Mr. Kim agreed to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump’s pledge to protect North Korea’s security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says it must first give up its nuclear weapons.
The United States has also refused to ease demands for international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insisted on 'denuclearization first', and increased the pressure on sanctions, achieved its goal in a high-pressure manner, and even refused to issue a 'war-ending declaration'," Li said.
