The new U.S.-Mexico-Canada trade deal will retain U.S. President Donald Trump’s ability to implement a 25 percent tariff threat on imported cars, while essentially exempting passenger cars, pickups and auto parts imported from Canada and Mexico from paying tariffs, according to a trade deal unveiled on Monday.
If Trump imposes so-called “Section 232” tariffs on cars for national security reasons, both Mexico and Canada will have a passenger car quota that is exempt from taxes on 2.6 million vehicles exported to the United States each year.
Under the subsidiary arrangement, pickups produced in both countries will be fully exempted from tariffs.
If Trump imposes auto tariffs, Mexico will get an annual $108 billion exemption from tax quotas for auto parts, and Canada will get a $32.4 billion quota.
Both quotas are well above the current level of production in both countries, providing room for growth for exports.
WASHINGTON/MEXICO, Sept 28 (Reuters) - After days of debate, Mexico said the administration of U.S. President Donald Trump and Canada are making concrete efforts to resolve trade policy differences that would make the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) expected to remain in the form of a tripartite agreement.
While details are lacking, the apparent progress is enough to prompt the Mexican and U.S. administrations to abruptly halt plans to publish the text of the two-party trade agreement, giving Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexican President-elect Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador told reporters in Mexico that the U.S. government had made new counter-proposals to the Canadian government and that he would continue to push all three countries to participate in NAFTA.
Mexican Economy Minister Ildefonso Guajardo said the time to submit the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement to Mexico and U.S. legislation was delayed because Canada and the U.S. government were “very serious” about trying to reach an agreement.
“Within the next 48 hours, we will know whether we will reach a text of a tripartite agreement or whether we will have to publish the text of the two-party agreement,” Guajardo said.
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian officials “in particular asked” to delay the release of the text.
A spokesman for the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S.-Mexico trade agreement and the U.S.-Canada consultations.
Officials in the Office of the Prime Minister of Canada and the Office of the Foreign Minister did not respond to requests for comment on counter-recommended comments.
According to foreign media reports, in a conservation center on the outskirts of Pretoria, South Africa's capital, two young lions play together, it is difficult to see any abnormality, but they are unique.
“This is the first chirop born in artificial insemination – the first pair in the world,” the University of Pretoria announced.
Scientists at the university are working on the reproductive system of the female female lion.
Ganswint, director of the Mammal Institute at the University of Pretoria, said the two cubs born on August 25 are quite healthy and normal.
After 18 months of intensive trials, his team finally achieved this breakthrough.
“We collected sperm from a healthy lion,” Ganswindt said in an interview with the media.
Next, the researchers waited for the lioness to have the right amount of hormone content to the right level, artificial insemination of it.
“Fortunately, the results were successful,” Ganswinter said.
Researchers "did several attempts, but unexpectedly, didn't take much effort," he said.
He said that the above-mentioned research breakthrough can be tested repeatedly, and scientists hope to use this technology to save the endangered big cats.
According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature, lions have been extinct in 26 African countries, and the total number of surviving wild lions has plummeted by 43% in the past 20 years, leaving only about 20,000.
The African lion is listed as a vulnerable animal by this organization.
"If we don't do something for this animal, they're going to be extinct," Ganswinter said.
He said the new technology does not require lions to be raised, but only if sperm is injected into a pregnant lioness, just as it has been done in North America and Europe against captive elephants.
South Korea’s exports fell in September, the biggest in more than two years, but analysts blamed fewer working days on the decline and said global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising U.S.-China trade tensions.
Indeed, South Korea’s average daily exports increased last month.
In addition, preliminary data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first few weeks of the long holiday.
South Korea's exports fell year-on-year in September, the largest since July 2016, down more than the 5.7 percent decline in the forecast of 11 analysts polled by Reuters.
Preliminary values released on Monday showed exports of $50.6 billion in September, down from $51.2 billion in August.
Despite concerns that the growing U.S.-China trade dispute could hurt other export-dependent Chinese neighbors, South Korea's exports to China rose 7.8% in September, expanding for the 23rd month in a row.
South Korea's exports to the United States fell 11.8 percent as oil sales fell.
Overseas sales of South Korean memory chips and petroleum products increased by 28.3 percent and 13.5 percent, respectively, despite concerns that the so-called “supercycle” of chips may have peaked.
“However, the impact of the trade conflict will be inevitable, as South Korea’s exports are heavily dependent on the U.S. and Chinese markets.”
Imports fell 2.1 percent to $4.08 billion, nor did they grow as seen in Reuters surveys by 3.1 percent.
The initial trade surplus in September was $9.7 billion, up from $6.9 billion in August.
The Ministry of Industry said that thanks to the United States and the European Union, the global manufacturing industry will remain prosperous, which is a favorable factor for South Korea's exports.
The statement pointed out that "the increase in export prices caused by the rise in oil prices will also be beneficial to exports in the second half of this year."
"However, the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with the increase in market volatility after the US interest rate hike, are the negative pressure on exports."
Exports increased to $2.6 billion on average in September and $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea's Mid-Autumn Festival this year falls on September 24-26, so September has only 19.5 working days, four days less than the same period last year.
South Korea's exports from January to September increased by 4.7% compared with the same period last year.
According to the Nikkei/Markit Purchasing Managers Index, South Korea’s manufacturing activity picked up in September, but was supported by domestic orders, which are likely to cloud the outlook for exports from China and Japan, as falling orders from China and Japan.
