Inner Mongolia import and export links 46 kinds of regulatory certificates all to achieve network verification - Sino-Singapore network
China News Network Hohhot November 5th (Reporter Li Aiping) Hohhot Customs said on the 5th that from now on, in addition to special circumstances such as confidentiality needs, all 46 kinds of regulatory certificates in the local import and export link have been verified online.
Inner Mongolia enterprises can use paperless methods to declare relevant documents to the customs, avoiding problems such as on-site rushing, paper applications, and repeated submissions in the past.
It is understood that the document preparation time refers to the preparation time of various documents required for the import and export link before the declaration of customs declaration, which is a major factor affecting the overall customs clearance time, and in order to reduce the customs clearance time and reduce the customs clearance cost, the document must be reduced.
Previously, the import and export links required customs verification of various kinds of regulatory documents up to 86, involving 19 departments.
It is reported that this time, in accordance with the principle of "cancellation, merger, can withdraw from the port of verification", relying on the international trade "single window" platform, customs and other 16 issuing authority system docking and data interconnection, to achieve more data run, enterprises less errands.
Customs said that in the past, enterprises need to submit paper applications back and forth to the on-site office hall of relevant departments, and the process is long and cannot track the status of the audit in real time.
Now enterprise users can directly log on to the "single window" portal for online applications.
After the approval of the issuing department, the electronic transmission of the certificate to the customs, and in the customs clearance link to achieve automatic comparison with the customs declaration data, intelligent verification, the audit results are unified through the "single window" feedback to the enterprise, to achieve the supervision of the document declaration, audit, customs clearance and feedback of the whole process of online processing.
Han seng chicken soup exports to China increased 20-fold in 4 years or related to the increase in the number of empty nest youth
Han ginseng chicken soup exports to China increased 20 times in 4 years Analysis: related to the increase in the number of empty nest youth
Yonhap News Agency reported on the 5th that South Korea's chicken soup exports to China last year exceeded 100,000 US dollars, a sharp increase of about 20 times compared with 2013 four years ago.
The analysis believes that this increase is related to the increase in the number of empty nest youth in China driving the hot sales of convenience food, as well as the increase in the attention of young people to nutritious meals.
The data was released by the Korea Agricultural and Aquatic Food Circulation Corporation (AT) on the 5th.
Last year, South Korea's exports of chicken soup to China reached 10.03.39 million US dollars, weighing 218.59 million kilograms, a sharp increase of 2094% and 3668.8% respectively compared with 2013.
The analysis believes that the increase in sales of chicken soup in South Korea in China is related to the increase in the increase of empty nest youth to promote the hot sales of convenience food, and the increase of young people's attention to nutritious meals.
As of this year, one-person households in China have exceeded the 200 million mark, and it is expected to increase to 30% of the total population in 2020, and local food companies have also targeted the "single food family" to launch various convenience foods.
In addition, the analysis also said that bird flu is the biggest factor hindering the rooting of chicken soup in the mainland Chinese market.
aT said that from November 2016 to April last year, there was a bird flu epidemic in South Korea, and the relevant departments completely banned the export of chicken soup to China, resulting in a sharp decline in exports.
In 2016, the export value of chicken soup to China reached 840,000 US dollars, and the export value plummeted to 100,000 US dollars last year due to avian influenza.
