WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. sanctions on Iran’s oil and financial sectors resumed on Monday, increasing pressure on Iran to limit Iran’s missile and nuclear programs and curb its growing military and political influence in the Middle East.
The move would reinstate U.S. sanctions lifted under the 2015 Iran nuclear deal, adding 300 new sanctions on Iran’s oil, shipping, insurance and banking sectors.
Details of the sanctions will be announced at a press conference at the 1330 GMT by Secretary of State Mike Pompeo and Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin.
The United States said it would temporarily allow eight importers to continue buying Iranian oil, including major buyers of Iranian oil such as China, India, South Korea, Japan and Turkey, to ensure that crude prices remain stable.
U.S. officials said the countries would put the money they pay Iran in an escrow account.
