TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) - Confidence among Japan’s large manufacturing players hit their lowest level in more than a year in the September quarter, according to a quarterly report released by the Bank of Japan on Monday, as rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affected production, putting companies at the pressure.
The survey barely shows that escalating global trade frictions have hit the confidence of large manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-blown trade war hitting the business outlook could threaten corporate capital spending.
Active capital spending is a bright spot in the Japanese economy.
The survey calls into question the Bank of Japan’s view that a solid economic expansion will help drive inflation to an accelerated 2 percent target, despite signs that companies are gradually passing costs on to customers.
"In the face of concerns caused by the global trade war, manufacturing confidence tends to stagnate due to slowing exports and weak factory production," said Nan Wuzhi, chief researcher of the China Metallurgical Institute of Agriculture and Forestry.
"Considence is still high. And because corporate earnings are improving and prices are rising, I don't think confidence will continue to decline."
The short-term survey showed that the index of large-scale manufacturing boom judgment in September fell from positive 21 three months ago to positive 19, which was a deterioration for the third consecutive quarter.
The median estimate for the market is positive 22.
In September, the large non-manufacturing boom judgment index fell to positive 22 from positive 24 in the June survey, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
The Reuters poll was positive for 22.
The survey shows that the large-scale manufacturing and non-manufacturing boom judgment index in December is expected to remain stable.
Investors are not concerned about the decline in the short-term corporate sentiment judgment index, and the Nikkei .N225 rose to a 27-year high on Monday as the yen continues to depreciate to help improve the export earnings prospects of Japanese companies.
Capital expenditure is stable.
While business confidence has declined, the latest short-term outlook highlights the soundness of corporate capital spending plans, helped by renewed capacity and increased investment in robotics and automation to cope with labor shortages caused by an aging population.
The central bank's short-term survey shows that large companies plan to increase capital spending by 13.4% in the current fiscal year ending in March 2019.
The previous short-term survey was 13.6%.
Nan said that all corporate capital expenditure plans to increase by 8.5% this fiscal year, close to the pace of the Japanese bubble economy.
“There is still room for further growth in capital spending, given that small businesses are raising their profit forecasts from now on, but that largely depends on the impact of the trade war on business confidence,” he said.
The short-term survey shows the increased ability of companies to pass on costs, with a positive output price index of 7, a decade high, an encouraging sign that Japan has made progress in its efforts to combat deflation.
The index, which measures the employment of large enterprises, hit negative 23, the most tight level since 1992, highlighting the tightening labor market.
Benefiting from strong corporate spending, the second quarter of the Japanese economy rebounded from its contraction in January-March.
But the escalation of the summer trade friction and the disruption of supply chains by natural disasters have clouded the economic outlook for Japan, which is dependent on exports.
