At present, the number of women in Brazil has reached 107 million, and if the women of all Brazil are gathered together to form a country, the country's population will rank 13th in the world, and the number of people will be more than twice the population of Spain.
In Brazil, women account for 52% of the total voters and 48% of men. Although the proportion of women among voters is very high, only 10% of women in Brazil's Congress.
Among the 193 countries in the world, Brazilian women are only ranked 154th in political participation, higher than in Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of struggle for rights, Brazilian women have still not succeeded in gaining their rights.
According to Brazilian sociologist Natalia Mori, this phenomenon exists because of the combination of ancient patrilineal societies, racism, and capitalist values.
“Political should be made up of citizens who advocate civil rights, status, access to public goods, and make up a society of multiple social groups. But Brazilian politics belongs to a monopoly of one group, and the majority of the population is not represented.”
A previous study by the Brazilian Locomotiva Institute also found that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that the politicians produced by the election can represent their rights, 90% of Brazilian women do not agree with the decisions made by politicians, and 93% of women do not agree with the current government policy.
