HONG KONG, Nov 5 (Reuters) - Hong Kong property prices fell for two consecutive months after peaking, and Hong Kong Monetary Authority President Chen Delin said on Monday that fashion needs time to observe whether the property market has entered a downward cycle, and if confirmed, it can be considered to relax the tightening policy of counter-cyclical measures in due course.
Chen Delin also pointed out that if the property price correction, the first to be affected will be the peak of the property market at the peak of the people, but is expected to appear as the 1997 Asian financial crisis when the property price fell sharply, the public sharply cut the price of the opportunity to sell the property is much lower.
Chen Delin, who led a number of senior HKMA executives to attend the Legislative Council briefing, said that if it is confirmed that the property market has entered a downward cycle, measures can be relaxed in the appropriate time.
"But now only a few weeks of data, relaxation is still too early, still need more time to see whether the property market into the downward cycle."
Since 10 years in 2009, the HKMA has launched eight rounds of counter-cyclical measures to significantly tighten the mortgages of various types of properties, including reducing the number of mortgages, and the need for mortgage applicants to pass rigorous stress tests to enhance bank risk management and earthquake resistance.
With Hong Kong officially entering the rate hike cycle, the whole Hong Kong private residential property price index peaked for two consecutive months in August-September, and the monthly decline in September widened to 1.44%.
However, the cumulative increase in the first three quarters of this year still reached 10.2%.
According to the HKMA data, the financial situation of households that measure Hong Kong's ability to face financial risks is still healthy. In the second quarter of this year, the proportion of Hong Kong households without mortgages reached 66%, higher than the average of 60% in 2009-11; the average number of new mortgages and the contribution-to-income ratio of new mortgages were 47% and 34%, respectively, compared with 64% and 41% in 2009-11.
However, Chen Delin said that the high anti-seismic ability does not mean that the residents of the real estate will not be damaged by the economic downturn, because the valuation of the property will fall, and those who buy a building at the peak will bear the brunt.
While the HKMA has tightened bank lending to mortgage lenders, home buyers can also obtain high-credit mortgages through mortgage insurance or mortgage loans provided by developers.
Chen Delin said that at present, together with the mortgage loans provided to developers, the number of mortgages for borrowers can reach 85-90%, and if the property price falls by 10%, there will be negative assets (i.e. the market value of the property falls below the level of the total outstanding mortgage loans).
However, the vice president of the HKMA, Nguyen Guoheng, pointed out that the authorities estimate that the total amount of mortgages provided by developers is only 2-2.5% of the total mortgages of banks, and the proportion is still low.
At the peak of negative assets in Hong Kong in 2003, the number of negative assets exceeded 100,000, accounting for 22% of the proportion of buildings.
As of the third quarter of this year, Hong Kong recorded zero negative assets for seven consecutive quarters.
