Systemic lupus is a chronic and difficult disease that affects multiple organs throughout the body, and has been considered an "incurable disease" in the past.
Because of its unknown pathogenesis, difficult diagnosis and treatment, the lack of effective treatment methods can not be cured.
Recently, Liu Wanli, a researcher at the School of Life Sciences of Tsinghua University, and Li Zhanguo, director of the rheumatism immunology center of Peking University People's Hospital, found that human immunoglobulins have molecular variants that increase the susceptibility of systemic lupus, and this variation is involved in regulating immune B cells.
In short, the two teams confirmed that an abnormal immune molecule in the human body is an important cause of systemic lupus.
According to Sun Xiaolin, one of the authors of the article, Sun Xiaolin of Peking University People's Hospital, the team collected nearly 2,000 large samples of systemic erythematosus patients and conducted research, and found that patients with immunoglobulin mutation produced a wide range of disease-causing cells and a large number of autoantibodies, and the incidence and severity of inflammation such as nephritis, arthritis, pyritis, and vasitis increased significantly.
Liu Wanli's team found that this immune molecular mutation activates the immune signaling pathway and promotes the pathogenesis of B cells to secrete a variety of autoantibodies through various research methods such as immune cell tracking, animal testing, and sequencing.
The reporter learned that the two teams are strong and united, giving full play to their respective advantages, and realizing the close combination of basic research and clinical applications.
Liu Wanli's team is committed to the immunorecognition and immune activation research of B lymphocytes, and the team of Li Zhanguo has long been engaged in clinical studies of systemic lupus.
"This study is one of the results of many years of cooperation between the two teams, and it is also the first time that academia has recognized in a mechanism that immunoglobulin gene abnormalities will induce systemic lupus, laying a solid foundation for further academic research and targeted treatment in clinical practice."
