Since the mid-2000s, as China’s demand for oilseeds has grown, Paul Thomas, a North Dakota farmer in the United States, has grown more and more soybeans in his field.
The transition peaked this year, with him planting 1,600 acres of soybeans on 5,000 acres, on an unprecedented scale.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch to the former staple food crop of the U.S. agricultural district in 2019: corn and wheat.
U.S. farmers have more soybeans than corn this year, the first time in 35 years.
The reason why it is planned to switch to other food crops is because U.S. farmers are facing difficulties selling soybeans in the context of US President Donald Trump's trade war against China.
China typically buys about 60 percent of U.S. soybeans, but because of the trade war, almost zero purchases of U.S. soybeans in recent months have pushed soybean prices to a 10-year low.
Thomas plans to grow more wheat next year, hoping to make more money by reducing his reliance on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Thomas said soybean prices "can give us a painful blow".
He said that without Chinese buying needs, the spot price of soybeans near his farm was $7.10 per bushel, while the price necessary to cover the cost was $8.50.
U.S. farmers have set record levels in soybean planting this year, and harvests are also expected to hit a record high.
At such a time as the impact, they were hit by a trade war.
In response to Trump's tariffs on imports of Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on imported U.S. soybeans in July.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture will release its first forecast for next year’s planting area, which is expected to include considerations on the impact of tariffs.
The forecast is expected to confirm private institutions' expectations of a reduction in soybean planting area.
According to a report seen by Reuters, Informa Economics predicted on October 19 that corn cultivation will increase by 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) in 2019 and soybean cultivation will be reduced by 7% to 83 million acres.
Informa also expects a 4% increase in U.S. wheat planting.
Soybeans planted before the retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, about 15 million acres higher than a decade ago.
Corn cultivation has increased by less than 5 million acres since 2008 to 89.1 million acres, and this year’s wheat planting area is 47.8 million acres, close to the lowest level in 100 years.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Cultration Association, has a total planting area of 3,600 acres, and this year he will spend nearly half of his time growing soybeans, but plans to cut them in the future.
He said it was possible to increase corn cultivation by up to 20 percent on his farm in northern Illinois, the largest soybean-growing state in the United States.
Soybeans yield less than corn per acre, but also require less fertilizer, which makes soybeans generally less expensive to grow.
If farmers move to final corn, they may raise costs, but will benefit some businesses, including the fertilizer sellers of Andersons Inc.
Andersons chief executive Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected the conversion of corn would benefit fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from the conversion of farmers to corn.
