BEIJING, Sept 30 (Reuters) - The Reserve Bank of China (PBOC) announced on Sunday that the central bank’s short position in foreign currency-to-local currency forward and futures contracts was zero for 12 consecutive months as of the end of August, and there were still no long positions in the month.
According to the previous data of the central bank, as of the end of August last year, the central bank held a total of US$6,044 million in short positions in foreign currency-to-local currency forward and futures contracts, unchanged for the fourth consecutive month; the short position valued in the SDR (Special Drawing Rights) was 4.276 billion SDR.
Since then, the central bank's foreign exchange long-term short position has been zero.
The central bank first released this data at the end of March 2016; the data show that the central bank's long position in foreign currency for local currency forward contracts and futures contracts at the end of February 2016 was $2.438 billion, and the short position was $28.9 billion.
The September data released at the end of October of the same year increased the net short by a net increase of $16.401 billion to $45.301 billion for the first time.
The central bank has previously said that the long-term and futures short positions of foreign currency on the local currency mainly reflect the forward operation of the central bank with commercial banks to meet the needs of the hedging of foreign currency liabilities of enterprises, and will continue to provide long-term safe-haven products according to the principle of real needs, and the long-term operation of the central bank will have a small impact on the scale of future foreign exchange reserves.
