This newspaper (intern reporter Li Qiyao) in recent years, there have been many cases of unqualified campus plastic runways.
To this end, the Ministry of Education issued a notice requiring that the new national standard be implemented at the surface sports venues of synthetic materials in primary and secondary schools delivered after November 1 this year.
The mandatory national standard "Synthetic Materials surface sports venue in primary and secondary schools" is led by the Ministry of Education, and 26 scientific research institutes and testing institutions participated in the drafting, after more than two years of revision, during which more than 100 expert meetings were organized, as well as nationwide field visits and sampling tests, and collected countless verification experiments on hundreds of enterprise products on the market.
The reporter found that the new national standard not only changed from "national recommended standards" to "national mandatory standards", but also added many contents, including thickness requirements, physical properties, aging resistance, inorganic filling content requirements, non-slip grain high-polymer content requirements, surface layer finished products harmful substances limit, non-solid and solid raw materials harmful substances limit.
In particular, it is worth mentioning that the new national standard has limited the harmful substances that may be produced in the construction of the campus plastic runway, from the original 7 items to 18 items, and stipulated the limit of volatile organic compounds on the completed runway in accordance with the home improvement standards.
For example, the release of harmful substances in the "currently watered and prefabricated surface layer finished products" clearly stipulates the release of harmful substances, requiring that the total volatile organic compounds should not be higher than 5 mg/m3, formaldehyde shall not be higher than 0.4 mg/m3, carbon disulfide shall not be higher than 7 mg/m3, benzene shall not be higher than 0.1 mg/m3, and the odor level shall not be higher than 3.
The new national standard also provides detailed provisions on sampling requirements, inspection rules, and judgment rules for plastic runways in primary and secondary schools.
In addition, the campus artificial turf is also included in the scope of compulsory testing of the national standard for the first time.
In the near future, all localities should carry out special work deployment on the implementation of the new national standard, and submit the implementation of the new national standard to the Ministry of Education's Department of Sports Health and Arts Education during the year.
